snippet.textDisplay: honestly I am not jealous of this lifestyle. I was looking at some alternative, but this thing has so many issues it's a constant work just to get by. u have to get fresh water, yes fresh water to use, then u have limited washing options. electricity is an issue, mobile signal, food, security and safety out there on the ocean, also environmental threats or rather unpredictable weather that can wreck this boat in no time, then there is a constant noise from the sea, limited sleep...etc etc and I can go on. I never lived or sailed, but I read and researched that lifestyle and I admire people who put up with it, because there is really nothing to envy about it even tho it look great, but that's only fraction of the picture

snippet.textDisplay: Newport sure IS America's biggest sailing community - at least the biggest with experienced sailors and racers anyway and the one with the MOST HISTORY as sailing was first POPULARIZED in Newport, RI and it was the first major seaport for the United States in the 1600s and early 1700s before Boston and New York. The majority of  132 years of the America's Cup races were sailed there until 1983 when  Australia ll beat Liberty skippered by Dennis Conner. I lived there for decades and watched the America's Cup defenders sail out of there going back to before the Newport Bridge was built. I remember seeing the crew of the Intrepid and Courageous almost daily walking around Bowen's Wharf after their practices. Some of the old wooden12 Meter boats and 100 foot long wooden J boats are are still there and have been turned into charter boats..

snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Elayna/Riley,
It may sound corny but... to slow his gringing habit, try massaging Lenny's jaw muscles (masseters) from his cheek bones to the lower edge of his jaw. These can be like thick strong rubber bands and Lenny's just discovering them! Try doing it for 3-5 minutes, once or twice a day... in a gentle rythmic roll from top to bottom, front to back. Circular motions. He may let you or he may not, but it's worth a try. Generally toddlers like it or even love it when their parents enjoy helping in a slow, gentle and pleasant way. It may take a few times before you'll notice an improvement, but it's the only thing that may help at this young age. You'll be amazed at those tiny yet firm muscles underneath all those cheeks! Massage out those tiny knots! Good Luck! Dr. Steve
